# Frontend UI/UX Consistency Guide

*This rule ensures consistent UI/UX across all frontend code.*

## Font Consistency

- **Use a single font family** throughout the application
- Define fonts in CSS, not inline styles
- Use system font stack or a single web font (Google Fonts, etc.)
- Avoid mixing multiple font families unless for specific design purposes
- Document the primary font in the main CSS file

## Emoji Usage

- **Limit emoji usage** - Use sparingly and consistently
- Prefer Font Awesome icons over emojis for UI elements
- If using emojis, use them consistently (same emoji for same concept)
- Avoid emojis in production UI unless part of the design system
- Use semantic HTML and CSS for visual elements when possible

## Icon Libraries

- **Choose one icon library** and stick with it (Font Awesome, Material Icons, etc.)
- Don't mix multiple icon libraries
- Use icon libraries consistently (same style throughout)
- Prefer icon libraries over emojis for UI elements

## JavaScript Organization

- **Avoid inline JavaScript** in HTML/Jinja templates
- Place JavaScript in external files
- Load JavaScript at the bottom of `<body>` or use `defer`/`async` attributes
- Organize JavaScript by functionality (not all in one file)
- Use modern ES6+ modules when possible
- Document JavaScript includes and their purposes

## CSS Organization

- **Avoid inline styles** - Use external CSS files or `<style>` blocks in `<head>`
- Organize CSS by component or page, not all in one file
- Use CSS variables for consistent colors, spacing, fonts
- Follow a CSS methodology (BEM, SMACSS, etc.) consistently
- Document CSS structure and naming conventions

## Template Consistency (Jinja/HTML)

- Use consistent template structure across pages
- Reuse components/templates when possible
- Keep template logic minimal (move complex logic to backend)
- Use consistent indentation and formatting
- Document template variables and their purposes

## Code Placement Standards

### HTML Structure
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <!-- CSS here -->
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css">
</head>
<body>
  <!-- Content here -->
  
  <!-- JavaScript at bottom -->
  <script src="app.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Jinja Structure
```jinja
{% extends "base.html" %}
{% block head %}
  <!-- CSS here -->
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="{{ url_for('static', filename='styles.css') }}">
{% endblock %}

{% block content %}
  <!-- Content here -->
{% endblock %}

{% block scripts %}
  <!-- JavaScript at bottom -->
  <script src="{{ url_for('static', filename='app.js') }}"></script>
{% endblock %}
```

## Anti-Patterns to Avoid

- ❌ Mixing inline styles with external CSS
- ❌ Inline JavaScript mixed with external scripts
- ❌ Multiple font families without clear purpose
- ❌ Excessive emoji usage
- ❌ Mixing icon libraries
- ❌ JavaScript in `<head>` (unless necessary with defer/async)
- ❌ CSS conflicts from multiple sources without organization

## Consistency Checklist

Before committing frontend code, ensure:
- [ ] Fonts are consistent across the page
- [ ] No inline styles (or minimal, well-justified)
- [ ] No inline JavaScript (or minimal, well-justified)
- [ ] JavaScript loaded at bottom or with defer/async
- [ ] CSS is organized and not conflicting
- [ ] Icons/emojis used consistently
- [ ] Template structure is consistent

---

*Customize this rule with your specific UI/UX preferences and design system.*
